My goal is to build a simple application to use as a basis for furthering my understanding of devops concepts

I decided to build a flask website that serves Jupyter Notebooks as a personal online programming reference containing project boilerplate code, links, and snippets. The initial site served a single static notebook page converted to html with Jupyter's built-in nbconvert functionality and was deployed on a linode vm.

Deploy to linode vm¶

Setup ssh in Remote Server

  • # ssh root@<ip_address>
  • # apt update && apt upgrade
  • # hostnamectl set-hostname <name>
  • # nano /etc/hosts (add ip and hostname)

/etc/hosts

127.0.0.1       localhost
<ip_address\>  <hostname\>
 The following lines are desirable for IPv6 capable hosts
::1     localhost ip6-localhost ip6-loopback
ff02::1 ip6-allnodes
ff02::2 ip6-allrouters
  • # adduser <username>
  • # adduser <username> sudo
  • # ssh <username>@
  • \$ mkdir ~/.ssh

Local Machine

  • \$ ssh-keygen -b 4096
  • \$ scp ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub <username>@<ip_address>:~/.ssh/authorized_keys

Remote Server

  • \$ sudo chmod 700 ~/.ssh/
  • \$ sudo chmod 600 ~/.ssh/*

Disable Root on Remote Server

  • \$ sudo nano /etc/ssh/sshd_config (PasswordAuthentication=no, PermitRootLogin=no)
  • \$ sudo systemctl restart sshd

Firewall for Remote Server

  • \$ sudo apt install ufw
  • \$ sudo ufw default allow outgoing
  • \$ sudo ufw default deny incoming
  • \$ sudo ufw allow ssh
  • \$ sudo ufw allow 5000
  • \$ sudo ufw enable
  • \$ sudo ufw status

After Installing Nginx

  • \$ sudo ufw allow http/tcp
  • \$ sudo ufw delete allow 5000

Create requirements.txt on Local Machine

  • \$ pip3 freeze > requirements.txt
  • \$ scp -r ~/<project_folder> <username>@<ip_address>:~/

Configure App on Remote Server

  • \$ sudo apt install python3-pip
  • \$ sudo apt install python3-venv
  • \$ python3 -m venv <<project_folder>/<environment_name>>
  • \$ cd <project_folder>
  • \$ source <environment_name>/bin/activate
  • \$ pip install -r requirements.txt

Optional

To create a json file for environment variables

  • \$ sudo touch /etc/confg.json
  • \$ sudo nano config.py Update to access environment variables from config.json with .get() method

Run Flask with Default server

  • \$ export FLASK_APP=<project_name>.py
  • \$ flask run --host=0.0.0.0

Install Nginx and Gunicorn on Remote Server

  • \$ sudo apt install nginx
  • \$ pip install gunicorn
  • \$ sudo rm /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/default
  • \$ sudo nano /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/<project_name>

Nginx configuration <project_name>

server {
    listen 80;
    server_name <ip_address>;
    location /static {
         alias /home/<username>/<project_folder>/static;
    }
    location / {
        proxy_pass http://localhost:8000;
        include /etc/nginx/proxy_params;
        proxy_redirect off;
    }

}

Update Firewall

  • \$ sudo ufw allow http/tcp
  • \$ sudo ufw delete allow 5000

Restart Nginx

  • \$ sudo systemctl restart nginx

Install Supervisor

  • \$ sudo apt install supervisor
  • \$ sudo nano /etc/supervisor/conf.d/<project_name>.conf

<project_name>.conf

[program:jupyter_page]
directory=/home/jmrobinson/jupyterpage
command=/home/jmrobinson/jupyterpage/jupyter_env/bin/gunicorn -w 3 jupyter_page>
user=jmrobinson
autostart=true
autorestart=true
stopasgroup=true
killasgroup=true
stderr_logfile=/var/log/jupyterpage/jupyterpage.err.log
stdout_logfile=/var/log/jupyterpage/jupyterpage.out.log

Create Log Files

  • \$ sudo touch /var/log/<project_name>/<project_name>.err.log
  • \$ sudo touch /var/log/<project_name>/<project_name>.out.log
  • \$ sudo supervisorctl reload

Encrypt with LetsEncrypt/Certbot

  • \$ sudo apt update
  • \$ sudo apt install software-properties-common
  • \$ sudo add-apt-repository universe
  • \$ sudo add-apt-repository ppa:certbot/certbot
  • \$ sudo apt update
  • \$ sudo apt install python-certbot-nginx The nginx config file may be updated to show domain instead of ip
  • \$ sudo certbot --nginx

Allow Https Traffic Through Firewall

  • \$ sudo ufw allow https

Simple Pipeline with Github, CircleCI, and Heroku¶

Jupyter Notebook changes are made, and saved. A script handles converting the Jupyter Notebook .ipynb files to html, syncronizing the changes made to the files in the ~/MyNotebooks directory to the copies in ~/myflasksite/app/templates directory where flask serves them from.

Test and Deploy sequence is triggered by a push to github master branch. CircleCI will run the test and deploy to Heroku

Shell script¶

#!bin/bash

### CONVERT SAVED JUPYTER NOTEBOOKS TO HTML WITH TABLE OF CONTENTS ###

cd /home/jrob/MyNotebooks

conda activate base
jupyter nbconvert --to html_toc mynotebook.ipynb
jupyter nbconvert --to html_toc dicebook.ipynb
conda deactivate

### UPDATE EXISTING HTML FILES IN APP/TEMPLATES ###

rsync /home/jrob/MyNotebook/mynotebook.html /home/jrob/myflasksite/app/templates/mynotebook.html
rsync /home/jrob/MyNotebook/dicebook.html /home/jrob/myflasksite/app/templates/dicebook.html


### PREPARE GIT PUSH TO MASTER FOR DEPLOYMENT VIA CIRCLECI AND HEROKU ###

git checkout master
git add -A
git commit -m "push to deploy"
git push github master

cd ~/

circleci config.yml¶

config.yml

version: 2.1
jobs:
  build:
    docker:
      - image: circleci/python:3.6.2-stretch-browsers
        environment:
          FLASK_CONFIG: testing
    steps:
      - checkout
      - run: mkdir test-reports
      - run:
          name: Install Python deps in a venv
          command: |
            python3 -m venv venv
            . venv/bin/activate
            pip install -r requirements.txt
      - run:
          name: Run Tests
          command: |
            . venv/bin/activate
            python test.py 
      - store_artifacts:
          path: test-reports/
          destination: tr1
      - store_test_results:
          path: test-reports/
  deploy:
    machine:
        enabled: true
    steps:
      - checkout
      - run:
          command: |
            git push https://heroku:$HEROKU_API_KEY@git.heroku.com/$HEROKU_APP_NAME.git master  
workflows:
  version: 2.1
  build-deploy:
    jobs:
      - build
      - deploy:
          requires:
            - build
          filters:
            branches:
              only: master

Flask api for local database¶

database_api.py

from flask import Flask
from flask_sqlalchemy import SQLAlchemy
from flask_marshmallow import Marshmallow
from flask_restful import Api, Resource

app = Flask(__name__)
app.config['SQLALCHEMY_DATABASE_URI'] = 'sqlite:///free-stuff.db'
db = SQLAlchemy(app)
api = Api(app)
ma = Marshmallow(app)

class Posts(db.Model):

    __tablename__ = "posts"

    timing = db.Column(db.String(120), unique=False, nullable=False, primary_key=True)
    title_text = db.Column(db.String(120), unique=False, nullable=False)
    price = db.Column(db.String(120), unique=False, nullable=False)
    link = db.Column(db.String(120), unique=False, nullable=False)

    def __repr__(self):
        return f"Posts('{self.timing}\n{self.title_text}\n{self.price}\n{self.link}\n')"

class PostsSchema(ma.SQLAlchemyAutoSchema):
    class Meta:
        model = Posts
        include_fk = True
post_schema = PostsSchema()
posts_schema = PostsSchema(many=True)

class PostsListResource(Resource):
    def get(self):
        posts = Posts.query.all()
        return posts_schema.dump(posts)
api.add_resource(PostsListResource, '/posts')

class PostsLastTen(Resource):
    def get(self):
        posts = Posts.query.all()
        last_ten = posts[-10:]
        return posts_schema.dump(last_ten[::-1])
api.add_resource(PostsLastTen, '/last-ten')

class OnePost(Resource):
    def get(self):
        posts = Posts.query.all()
        last_post = posts.pop()
        return post_schema.dumps(last_post)
api.add_resource(OnePost, '/last-one')


if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(host='localhost',port=5001)

test.py¶

import app
import unittest


class MyTestCase(unittest.TestCase):

    def setUp(self):
        app.app.testing = True
        self.app = app.app.test_client()

    def test_home(self):
        response = self.app.get('/')
        self.assertEqual(response.status_code, 200)

    def test_myscrapbook(self):
        response = self.app.get('/myscrapbook')
        self.assertEqual(response.status_code, 200)

    def test_freestuff_app_book(self):
        response = self.app.get('/freestuff_app_book')
        self.assertEqual(response.status_code, 200)

    def test_dicebook(self):
        response = self.app.get('/dicebook')
        self.assertEqual(response.status_code, 200)

    def test_apibook(self):
        response = self.app.get('/apibook')
        self.assertEqual(response.status_code, 200)



if __name__ == "__main__":
    unittest.main()

routes.py (formerly views.py)¶

import requests
import json
from flask import render_template,url_for
from app import app

@app.route('/')
@app.route('/home')
def home():
    return render_template('home.html')

@app.route('/myscrapbook')
def myscrapbook():
    return render_template('mynotebook.html')

@app.route('/freestuff_app_book')
def freestuff_app_book():
    return render_template('freestuff_app_book.html')

@app.route('/dicebook')
def dicebook():
    return render_template('dicebook.html')

@app.route('/apibook')
def apibook():
    return render_template('apibook.html')

@app.route('/lasttenresults')
def lasttenresults():
    results = requests.get('http://localhost:5001/last-ten')
    return render_template('lasttenresults.html', results=json.loads(results.text))

Added a volume to the Dockerfile¶

FROM python:3.8-slim-buster
WORKDIR /myapp
COPY . /myapp
ENV FLASK_APP=main.py
RUN pip3 install -r requirements.txt

EXPOSE 5000
CMD ["flask", "run", "--host=0.0.0.0"]

Made a Jenkinsfile pipeline to push docker image of site to dockerhub¶

node {
    stage('SCM Checkout'){
        git 'git@github.com:jmrobinsonma/myflasksite.git'
    }
    stage('Building'){
        sh 'python3 -m venv venv'
        sh '. venv/bin/activate'
        sh 'pip3 install -r requirements.txt'
    }
    stage('Testing'){
        sh 'python3 test.py'
    }
    stage('Docker build'){
        sh 'docker build -t jmrobinson/myflasksite .'
    }
    stage('Push Docker image'){
        withCredentials([string(credentialsId: 'dockerpass', variable: 'DOCKERPWD')]) {
            sh "docker login -u jmrobinson -p ${DOCKERPWD}"
        }
        sh 'docker push jmrobinson/myflasksite'
    }
}
